TI  - D2.2: CVDLINK Full System Design [Abstract]
AU  - Crucianu, Iacob
AU  - Augustauskas, Rytis
AU  - Parviainen, Anna
AU  - Raptopoulos, Andreas
AU  - Haidamous, Jad
T2  - Zenodo (CERN European Organization for Nuclear Research)
AB  - The following deliverable is currently under review by the European Commission and will be published in full once it is approved. Abstract: The current report describes the architecture design for CVDLINK platforms. The architecture was designed around a federative approach that addresses long-standing challenges in cardiovascular research, particularly related to data fragmentation, privacy, and interoperability. Recognising that patient data is often distributed across multiple institutions and jurisdictions, CVDLINK adopts a federated data model where data remains at its source, under the full control of its owner, while still enabling collaborative research and artificial intelligence (AI)-based tools experimentation across borders. The federated architecture is composed of a central coordinating node and multiple subordinate nodes, each equipped with its own local data processing, security, and AI components. The central node orchestrates communication, aggregates anonymized model updates, and provides shared services such as federated search, virtual dataset generation, and shared AI tool repositories. This layered architecture ensures scalability, resilience, and controlled participation - nodes can join, leave, or limit access to data at any time. Semantic interoperability is achieved through alignment with common data models (CDMs), such as OMOP and HL7 FHIR, while metadata and FAIR principles enable rich data discovery without exposing raw datasets. Federated nodes also support role-based access and auditing to ensure security and traceability across the data lifecycle. By combining federated learning, semantic harmonization, and secure orchestration, CVDLINK pioneers a new paradigm for large-scale, collaborative cardiovascular research. It empowers institutions to contribute to AI innovation without compromising autonomy, privacy, or clinical workflows, setting a benchmark for ethical and effective digital health infrastructure across Europe. -- Funded by the European Union. Views and opinions expressed are however those of the author(s)only and do not necessarily reflect those of the European Union or the European Health and Digital Executive Agency. Neither the European Union nor the granting authority can be held responsible for them.
